Here is the OpenAPI-detectable information for the endpoint tied to PostLikeController@destroy (the delete like action):

- Full HTTP request path: /posts/{post}/likes
  - Path parameter: {post} represents the Post model (usually the post ID)

- Are all HTTP methods acceptable for this path? No
  - There is more than one route for this path in routes/auth.php:
    - POST /posts/{post}/likes -> PostLikeController@store
    - DELETE /posts/{post}/likes -> PostLikeController@destroy

- HEAD: false
  - The route is defined for POST and DELETE. HEAD is not automatically provided for non-GET routes in this codebase.

- POST: true
  - Route::post('/posts/{post}/likes', [PostLikeController::class, 'store']) exists.

- OPTIONS: false
  - No OPTIONS route is defined for this path in the code.

- TRACE: false
  - No TRACE route is defined for this path.

- GET: false
  - There is no GET route for /posts/{post}/likes.

- PUT: false
  - There is no PUT route for /posts/{post}/likes.

- DELETE: true
  - Route::delete('/posts/{post}/likes', [PostLikeController::class, 'destroy']) exists.

- PATCH: false
  - There is no PATCH route for /posts/{post}/likes.

Explanation:
- The endpoint for removing a like (destroy) is defined via DELETE at /posts/{post}/likes, and there is also a POST route at the same path for adding a like. No other HTTP methods are defined for this path in the provided routes file, so only POST and DELETE are supported. The endpoints are grouped under middleware requiring authentication and email verification, meaning only authenticated and verified users can invoke these actions. HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, GET, PUT, PATCH are not implemented for this path in the code.
